Key terms 
Internet of Things (IoT): A network of linked devices capable of exchanging data and communicating through the internet.
Smart Home: A residential environment where appliances are digitally controlled, monitored and automated.
Blynk: A mobile IoT platform used for device monitoring, control and dashboard visualisation.
PIR Sensor: A Passive Infrared Sensor used to detect motion based on infrared radiation changes.
DS3231 Real-Time Clock (RTC): A hardware module which provides accurate time for scheduling and automation tasks.
Servo Motor: A rotary actuator used in this project for door unlock and lock control.
Energy Consumption: The amount of electrical energy used by appliances with time, measured in watt-hours (Wh).
Energy Saving Percentage: A calculated value symbolising the efficiency of appliance usage based on device activity.










1. Introduction
1.1 Background and Context
In modern households the expanding use of electrical appliances has considerably contributed to rising energy consumption globally. Domestic appliances such as lighting systems, fans and electronic devices increase comfort and convenience; however, inefficient usage and lack of monitoring often result in unnecessary electricity wastage. Often, appliances remain switched on longer than necessary due to human forgetfulness, absence of automation and limited awareness of real-time energy consumption. Since energy costs and environmental concerns are increasing, there is a increasing demand for intelligent systems which can monitor, control and optimise household energy usage effectively. (Rehman et al. 2025).
Recent developments in the Internet of Things (IoT) have assisted the development of smart home systems which can integrate actuators, sensors and wireless communication technologies via a single connected environment. These systems let users to remotely control and monitor household devices by using smartphones applications. Smart home automation not only increase user convenience but also encourages energy conservation, safety and efficient resource management (Condon et al. 2023).
This project, titled “An Edge-Computing Approach to Energy Conservation: Developing a Predictive Resource Management System for Smart Homes,” focused on the design and implementation of an IoT-based smart home energy management system which combines remote device control, automation, motion detection, notification services and real-time energy monitoring within an integrated mobile platform. The implemented system allow users to control appliances including fans, lights and a servo motor-based door lock remotely via the Blynk mobile application.
The system integrates a PIR motion sensor to detect movement and display live motion status within the mobile dashboard. Moreover, the project combined a DS3231 Real-Time Clock module, which enables accurate real-time automation and scheduling. By using the RTC module, the system complies with automated operations including switching OFF all connected devices automatically, turning lights ON at configured times and generating reminder notifications before shutdown events occur.
A significant expansion of the implemented system is the involvement of dynamic time configuration directly from the mobile application. Instead of modifying source code manually, users can set up automation settings such as all-device shutdown time, reminder notification timing, automatic light ON time, light alert duration and fan auto-OFF duration directly via Blynk widgets and DataStream’s. This enhances flexibility, usability and real-time communication between users and the smart home environment.
The system also consists of energy-saving and intelligent safety features. For example, lights and fans automatically turn OFF after predefined durations to skip unnecessary power consumption. Additionally, the application uninterruptedly calculates energy consumption in watt-hours (Wh) based on predefined power ratings and appliance operation time. Moreover, the system calculates a saved energy percentage to signify the efficiency level of appliance usage.
To enhance user interaction and awareness, the Blynk mobile dashboard displays real-time information such as motion detection, automation schedules, energy usage, appliance status, saved energy percentage and adjustable alert durations. Data visualisation is achieved via live charts and gauge widgets, by allowing users to monitor consumption trends effectively.
The project integrates various technologies including Embedded C++, Arduino, WiFi communication, PIR sensors, servo motors, the DS3231 RTC module and the Blynk IoT platform. Simultaneously, these technologies produce a low-cost and efficient smart home prototype which shows the practical application of IoT and automation for domestic energy management (Bindushree G T 2022).
1.2 Problem Statement
One of the considerable challenges in modern households is inefficient energy management caused by manual appliance control, shortage of automation and insufficient awareness of energy consumption. Devices such as fans and lights are frequently left operating excessively, leading to extended energy waste and electricity costs. Traditional home systems do not offer users with real-time monitoring, automated scheduling or intelligent safety mechanisms to manage appliance usage efficiently (Molla 2020).
Although many commercial smart home systems persist, they are mostly expensive, dependent on cloud infrastructure or complex. In addition, several systems provide limited user flexibility regarding real-time monitoring and automation configuration system. Numerous low-cost systems also lack integrated energy visualisation, notification services and dynamic scheduling features (Saker and surah al dakhl 2017).
This project addresses this issue by developing a smart home energy management system which integrates RTC-based automation, motion detection, remote appliance control, notification services and real-time energy monitoring within a single mobile application. The system aims to provide an affordable and practical solution for reducing unnecessary electricity consumption and improving household energy efficiency.
1.3 Aim of the Project
The main aim of this project is to design, implement and evaluate an IoT-enabled smart home energy management system able of performing real-time energy monitoring, intelligent appliance automation and remote device control via a mobile application platform. The project additionally aims to reduce unnecessary electricity consumption through automated safety features, RTC-based scheduling and user-centred energy management functionality evaluated through participant usability testing (Rehman et al. 2025)
1.4 Objectives
The objectives of this project are:
	To develop a smart home system qualified of remotely controlling fans, lights and a door locking mechanism via a mobile application. 
	To integrate display real-time motion status and PIR-based motion detection within the application. 
	To implement RTC-based automation by using the DS3231 module for scheduled appliance control. 
	To develop a dynamic mobile-based configuration system which allows users to adjust automation timings without altering the source code. 
	To execute a notification system that alerts users regarding automation events and appliance activity. 
	To develop automatic safety mechanisms including automatic light OFF, fan OFF and complete device shutdown. 
	To display and calculate real-time energy consumption and saved energy percentage. 
	To visualise system data by using charts, live graphs and dashboard widgets within the Blynk application. 
	To evaluate the efficiency of the implemented system in reducing unnecessary appliance usage and improving energy awareness. 
1.5 Research Question
The main research question guiding this project is:
“How can an IoT-based smart home system merging remote control, real-time monitoring, RTC-based automation and intelligent energy management reduce unnecessary power consumption and improve household energy efficiency?”
This research investigates whether combining mobile interaction, automation and energy awareness features within a low-cost IoT framework can offer an effective and practical smart home energy management solution.
1.6 Scope of the Project
The scope of this project is restricted to the design and implementation of a prototype based smart home energy management system using IoT technologies. The system contains remote control of fans, light and a servo motor door lock via the Blynk mobile application. It also incorporates DS3231 RTC-based scheduling, PIR motion detection, automatic safety features, notification services and real-time energy monitoring.
The project concentrates on demonstrating energy management functionalities and smart automation rather than producing a full commercial smart home ecosystem. Energy calculations are established on operational durations and predefined power ratings rather than direct electrical sensor measurements. Additionally, advanced technologies including voice assistants, machine learning-based prediction and cloud analytics are beyond the scope of this project but might be considered for future enhancement. (Molla 2020)

2. Literature Survey
2.1 Introduction to Smart Home and IoT Technologies
(Pandey et al. 2025) identified IoT as a framework that integrates sensors, communication protocols and embedded devices to support real-time data collection and automation. Similarly, Risteska Stojkoska and Trivodaliev (2017) reported that smart home technologies can improve convenience and support energy optimisation through intelligent appliance management.
However, many existing smart home implementations focus primarily on connectivity and remote access rather than demonstrating measurable energy-saving outcomes. Furthermore, several studies discuss smart home concepts at a theoretical level without providing integrated solutions that combine automation, monitoring and energy awareness. This creates a need for affordable systems capable of delivering both appliance automation and energy management functionality. The proposed system addresses this gap by integrating remote control, motion detection, scheduling and energy monitoring within a single mobile-based platform. (Martínez-Morocho et al. 2026)
2.2 Edge Computing in Smart Home Systems
(Sannapureddy et al. 2024) argued that edge computing improves responsiveness by processing data closer to devices rather than relying entirely on cloud infrastructure. Similarly, (Zhang et al. 2025) found that localised processing reduces latency and improves reliability in IoT environments requiring real-time decision making.
Although cloud-based architectures provide scalability and remote accessibility, they remain dependent on internet connectivity and may introduce privacy and latency concerns. Habibi et al. (2020) demonstrated that local processing can improve operational efficiency and reduce unnecessary external communication. However, some proposed edge architectures rely on specialised gateways and high-performance hardware, increasing implementation costs. The proposed system addresses this limitation by using an Arduino Uno R4 WiFi controller to perform automation and monitoring functions locally while maintaining a low-cost deployment model.

2.3 Smart Home Automation and Appliance Control
Al-Kuwari et al. (2018) reported that smart home automation systems improve convenience and energy efficiency through the integration of sensors, relay modules and wireless communication technologies. Many existing systems also provide remote appliance control through mobile applications, allowing users to monitor and manage devices in real time.
Despite these advantages, several low-cost automation systems require source-code modifications whenever scheduling changes are needed, limiting accessibility for non-technical users. This represents a usability limitation within many existing implementations. To address this issue, the proposed system incorporates dynamic mobile-based scheduling, enabling users to modify automation timings directly through the mobile application without reprogramming the controller. This improves flexibility and usability compared with many basic IoT automation solutions.
2.4 Motion Detection and Real-Time Monitoring
Odamboy Djumanazarov et al. (2022) demonstrated that PIR sensors provide a low-cost and reliable method for detecting human movement in smart home environments. Their findings suggest that motion-based automation can improve energy efficiency by ensuring appliances operate only when required. However, many existing systems focus primarily on motion detection while providing limited real-time user feedback and monitoring capabilities. This reduces user awareness of system activity and appliance usage.
To address this limitation, the proposed system integrates PIR-based motion detection with live dashboard updates through the Blynk platform, enabling users to monitor occupancy conditions and automation events in real time.

2.5 Energy Monitoring and Energy Management Systems
Energy management is one of the most notable research areas within smart home development. Smart home energy management systems intend to reduce electricity wastage by improving user awareness and monitoring appliance consumption.
According to International Energy Agency (2022), residential buildings provide substantially to global electricity consumption. The report illustrates the importance of automation systems and smart technologies in improving household energy efficiency. Aliero et al. (2021) reported that smart home energy management systems can reduce energy waste through the integration of monitoring and automation technologies. However, many existing solutions rely on specialised sensors and costly infrastructure, limiting accessibility for domestic users.
This project addresses this limitation through a lightweight energy-monitoring approach that estimates energy consumption using appliance operating duration and predefined power ratings. The calculated values are displayed through charts, gauges and indicators within the mobile dashboard to improve user awareness of energy usage.

2.6 Notification Systems and Intelligent Safety Features
Notification systems are increasingly integrated into modern smart home environments to improve safety and user awareness. Mobile notifications can alert users regarding security events, appliance activity or energy-related warnings.
Existing research demonstrates that many low-cost IoT systems lack of intelligent safety controls and integrated alert mechanisms. In some systems, appliances may continue to operate unnecessarily if users forget to switch them OFF manually.
The implemented system addresses this limitation through notification services and intelligent safety features. The application sends notifications for events including:
	lights remaining ON for extended periods, 
	reminder alerts before automatic shutdown, 
	automatic all-device OFF confirmation. 
The system also provides automatic light OFF and fan OFF features after configurable durations. These automation mechanisms help to reduce unnecessary power consumption while improving operational efficiency and household safety.
2.7 Research Gap and Justification of the Proposed System
The literature review identified several limitations within existing smart home energy management solutions. While many studies successfully demonstrate remote appliance control, automation and monitoring capabilities, these functionalities are often implemented independently rather than within a single integrated platform. Cloud-dependent architectures introduce concerns relating to latency, privacy and internet reliability, whereas some advanced edge-computing solutions require specialised hardware that increases cost. Furthermore, many low-cost systems provide limited user configurability, requiring manual source-code modifications to update automation schedules. Existing solutions also frequently lack integrated energy visualisation, notification services and intelligent safety features. These limitations highlight a research gap for an affordable, user-friendly smart home system that combines automation, energy monitoring, real-time visualisation and dynamic mobile-based configuration within a unified platform. (Alejandro Valencia Arias et al. 2023)


 
