3.1.2 Hardware Implementation
 

 


The smart home prototype was implemented by using Arduino as the primary microcontroller platform. Arduino was selected due to its affordability, ease of programming and compatibility with multiple IoT modules and sensors.
The hardware components used in the project consist of: Arduino microcontroller, PIR motion sensor, DS3231 Real-Time Clock (RTC) module, Servo motor, Relay modules, LED lighting components, Fan module, WiFi communication module 
The PIR sensor was integrated to detect human movement and send motion status data to the mobile application. The servo motor was selected to simulate a smart door lock mechanism, while relay modules-controlled appliance switching operations. The DS3231 RTC module supplied accurate real-time scheduling for automation tasks.
Each hardware component was primarily tested separately before being integrated into the final system. This confirmed reliable communication between actuators, sensors and the microcontroller. (Sreejith et al. 2025)


3.1.3 Software Development
 
The software implementation was developed by using Embedded C/C++ within the Arduino IDE environment. The system logic contained device control functions, notification triggers automation algorithms and energy calculations.
The Blynk IoT platform was used to create enable wireless communication and the mobile dashboard between the smart home system and the user. Blynk was selected since it provides: real-time IoT communication, mobile dashboard widgets, graph visualisation, notification services, adjustable data streams. 
The Blynk dashboard was designed to incorporate: appliance control buttons, motion detection indicators, automation timing controls, energy monitoring gauges, live graph visualisations, notification settings. 
Dynamic automation settings were implemented by using Blynk datastreams, authorising users to configure scheduling values directly from the mobile application without modifying Arduino source code. This confirmed a reliable communication between sensors, actuators and the microcontroller. (Sharma1 and Kantha 2020)
 
 
