3.1.4 RTC-Based Automation Method
A considerable methodology component involved implementing RTC-based automation by using the DS3231 module. The RTC module continuously supplied accurate hour and minute values to the microcontroller.
Automation rules were developed to: turn lights ON automatically at configured times, switch OFF all devices at scheduled times, trigger reminder notifications before shutdown, perform automatic fan OFF operations after configured durations. 
The integration of RTC automation improved system intelligence and reduced the need for continuous manual appliance management. Compared to simple timer-delay components, RTC scheduling provided more user-configurable and accurate automation behaviour. (Telsang et al. 2024)
	Energy Monitoring Method
The energy monitoring functionality was implemented by using a software-based calculation method. Rather than using dedicated electrical current sensors, energy consumption was estimated by using: appliance power ratings, ON/OFF device states, duration of operation. The energy calculation observed the formula:Energy (Wh)=Power (W)×Time (hours). The system continuously calculated and monitored appliance runtime on daily energy usage in watt-hours (Wh). Additionally, an energy-saving percentage was produced dynamically based on appliance activity levels.
This lightweight monitoring approach was selected since it reduced hardware complexity and cost while providing meaningful energy awareness for users. (International Energy Agency 2022)
3.2 System Testing and Evaluation
3.2.1 Quantitative Evaluation
Quantitative evaluation was conducted to measure system performance and user satisfaction using numerical data and structured survey responses. A Likert-scale questionnaire was distributed to participants following a live demonstration of the smart home prototype at Southampton Solent University. The questionnaire collected measurable feedback regarding usability, automation effectiveness, energy monitoring and remote-control functionality. User evaluation results indicated that 90% of participants agreed that the system increased energy awareness and supported more efficient appliance usage. Quantitative findings are presented and analysed further in Chapter 5. (Joshi and Das 2025)
3.2.2 Qualitative Evaluation
Qualitative evaluation was conducted to gather participant opinions, experiences and observations regarding the implemented smart home system. Participants were encouraged to provide feedback after interacting with the prototype, particularly regarding automation convenience, mobile dashboard usability and energy-monitoring functionality.
Feedback indicated that participants found the system easy to use and appreciated the automatic device control and real-time monitoring features. Several participants additionally suggested future improvements including voice assistant integration and advanced predictive automation capabilities. Qualitative participant feedback is discussed further in the Results chapter. (Joshi and Das 2025)
3.2.3 Functional Testing
Functional testing was carried out though development to verify that all hardware and software components operated correctly. Individual feature was tested independently before full system integration.
The following functionalities were verified: light ON/OFF control, fan ON/OFF control, servo motor door control, PIR motion detection, RTC scheduling operations, mobile notifications, energy calculations, graph visualisation, automatic device shutdown. 
The testing process verified that user commands sent through the Blynk application correctly controlled the connected appliances in real time.

3.2.4 Automation Testing
Automation testing concentrated on evaluating the reliability and accuracy of RTC-based scheduling features.
Testing contained: automatic light activation at configured times, automatic device shutdown, triggering of reminder notification, fan auto-OFF timing, light alert duration monitoring. 
Automation Testing Area	Purpose
Automatic light activation	Verify light turns ON at configured RTC time
Automatic device shutdown	Verify all devices switch OFF automatically
Reminder notification triggering	Verify reminder alerts are generated correctly
Fan auto-OFF timing	Verify fan switches OFF after configured duration
Light alert duration monitoring	Verify alerts trigger when light remains ON too long

The DS3231 RTC module was tested frequently to confirm stable and accurate scheduling performance. (Vadan and Miclea 2023)
3.2.5 Energy Monitoring Evaluation
The energy monitoring system was analysed by comparing device runtime against calculated energy values. Appliance operation durations were monitored manually and compared with displayed energy consumption values within the Blynk dashboard.
Graphs and gauge widgets were used to visualise daily energy usage, saved energy percentage, patterns of appliance activity. The results established that the system successfully tracked usage trends and provided energy awareness information.

	User Evaluation Procedure
Basic user evaluation was conducted to assess the usability, accessibility, and effectiveness of the developed smart home energy management system. The evaluation focused on: ease of navigation, readability of information, simplicity of device control, responsiveness of automation features, clarity of energy visualisation and overall user satisfaction. 
A live demonstration of the prototype system was physically conducted at Southampton Solent University. Participants were invited to interact with the smart home system, including the mobile dashboard, motion detection features, RTC-based automation, appliance control functions, and energy monitoring capabilities.
Following the demonstration, participants completed an anonymous Jisc Online Survey questionnaire. The questionnaire was designed to gather user opinions regarding usability, automation performance, energy awareness, and overall effectiveness of the developed system.
Participation was voluntary and anonymous, and no personally identifiable information was collected. Ethical considerations were maintained by providing participants with a consent form and participant information page before beginning the survey.
The collected feedback was later analysed using percentage-based response summaries and graphical visualisations generated through the Jisc survey platform. The evaluation results were used to assess the practicality and usability of the proposed smart home solution. (Govindarajan et al. 2025)
