3.3 Professional, Legal and Ethical Issues
The project was developed whilst considering legal, professional and ethical responsibilities associated with IoT systems and smart home technologies.
3.3.1 Ethical Considerations
Ethical approval for the project was obtained throughout Southampton Solent University’s ethics application process and is included in the appendices of this report.The project primarily processes device activity and environmental data rather than personally identifiable information. Motion detection data collected via the PIR sensor which only indicates movement presence and does not capture audio recordings, images or biometric information. Any user feedback collected during system evaluation was anonymised and voluntary. Participants were informed regarding the aim of testing and retained the right to withdraw at any stage.
Prior to conducting participant-based evaluation and data collection, the researcher successfully completed the Epigeum “Working with Human Participants” training course provided through Southampton Solent University. The certification confirmed understanding of ethical research practices, participant consent procedures, confidentiality, anonymity and responsible data collection involving human participants. This training supported the ethical management of the user evaluation process conducted within this project. A copy of signed ethics form by the supervisor and the completion certificate is provided in Appendix B.
3.3.2 GDPR and Data Privacy
The project followed UK GDPR principles and data privacy requirements throughout development phase. The system was designed to reduce collection of personal information. No sensitive personal data was kept permanently within the system. The Blynk application was only used for monitoring and appliance control purposes. Authentication and account management were controlled through the Blynk platform infrastructure. The project also minimised privacy concerns by processing automation logic locally on the microcontroller rather than constantly transmitting all sensor data to external cloud servers.
3.3.3 Accessibility and Usability
The mobile dashboard interface was designed with accessibility and usability principles in mind. Although the project does not execute a full web-based GUI, dashboard elements were organised clearly to enhance readability and interaction. Consideration was given to simple navigation, readable labels, logical widget grouping, real-time feedback visibility. The design method aligns with usability concepts associated with the W3C Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI) and WCAG accessibility recommendations.
3.3.4 Professional Standards
The project followed research practices and professional software development throughout implementation. Academic integrity was sustained through proper Harvard referencing and citation of literature sources. Testing procedures, development progress and system changes were documented systematically during implementation phase. Modular coding approaches were used to minimise improve maintainability and software errors. (Karale 2021)
