This section discusses the development, design and implementation of the proposed smart home energy management system. It explains the architecture of the hardware and software selection, mobile dashboard development, implementation process and testing procedures. Furthermore, this section also discusses the challenges encountered during development and how these issues were determined.
The design of the system concentrated on creating a user-friendly, low-cost and energy-efficient smart home prototype qualified for real-time monitoring, remote appliance control and intelligent automation. The system integrates actuators, sensors, communication modules and mobile technologies to create an IoT-enabled smart home environment.
	System Design Overview
The proposed smart home system was designed by using an IoT-based architecture where actuators, sensors and mobile applications communicate through wireless internet connectivity. The design aim was to create a system capable of: remotely controlling household devices, monitoring appliance activity in real time, automating appliance behaviour, reducing unnecessary energy consumption, providing energy awareness through live visualisation. (Ma’arif et al. 2023)
The system architecture consists of four major layers:
	Hardware Layer 
	Control and Processing Layer 
	Communication Layer 
	User Interface Layer 
The hardware layer includes the physical devices including relays, sensors, servo motors and RTC modules. The processing layer consists of the Arduino-compatible microcontroller responsible for executing energy calculations and automation logic. The communication layer operates wireless connectivity through WiFi and the Blynk cloud platform. Finally, the user interface layer include the Blynk mobile dashboard used for monitoring and device control.
The architecture was designed to support both automated and manual appliance management while maintaining low implementation operational simplicity and cost.

 
