The DS3231 RTC module was selected over older RTC versions because it provides significantly improved timing accuracy through its integrated temperature-compensated crystal oscillator (TCXO). Unlike older modules such as the DS1307, the DS3231 is less affected by environmental temperature variations and maintains stable long-term timekeeping performance. This made the module more suitable for automation features requiring accurate scheduling, including automatic light activation, reminder notifications and automatic all-device shutdown operations.
The RTC module enabled: automatic light ON scheduling, automatic all-device OFF scheduling, reminder alert timing, fan auto-OFF operations. (Suryamiharja et al. 2025)
4.2.4 Servo Motor Selection
The smart home system required an actuator capable of performing door locking and unlocking operations. Several actuator technologies were considered during system design, including DC motors, stepper motors and servo motors. Following evaluation, a servo motor was selected as the most suitable solution for the proposed smart home prototype. 
Figure 3.6: Servo Motor Used for Smart Door Lock Control
Comparison of Actuator Types
Actuator	Advantages	Limitations
DC Motor	Simple rotation	No positional accuracy
Stepper Motor	Precise movement	More complex control
Servo Motor	Accurate angle positioning	Limited rotation range
The servo motor was selected because it provides precise angle control, stable rotational positioning, low power consumption and simple integration with Arduino systems. Unlike DC motors, servo motors can accurately maintain fixed angular positions, making them suitable for controlled door locking and unlocking operations. Although stepper motors also provide accurate movement control, they require more complex programming and hardware configuration compared with servo motors.
The servo motor was particularly appropriate for this project because the door mechanism only required controlled angular movement rather than continuous rotation. The actuator was integrated with the Blynk mobile application, allowing users to remotely lock and unlock the smart door mechanism through the mobile dashboard interface.
	Relay Module Selection
Relay modules were implemented within the smart home energy management system to control high-power appliances including the lighting components and fan module. Different switching technologies were evaluated during system design, including transistor switching circuits, MOSFET modules and relay modules. Following comparison, relay modules were selected as the most suitable solution for appliance automation within the proposed system.
 
Figure 3.4 Relay module used for appliance switching.    
Comparison of Switching Technologies
Switching Technology	Advantages	Limitations
Transistor Switching	Fast switching speed, low cost	Limited support for high-voltage AC appliances
MOSFET Modules	Efficient power control, low heat generation	More suitable for DC loads and requires additional protection circuitry
Relay Modules	Electrical isolation, supports higher-voltage loads, easy integration with Arduino	Slower switching speed compared with transistor-based solutions
                                     
Relay modules were selected because they provide electrical isolation between the low-voltage Arduino controller and higher-power electrical circuits. In addition, relay modules support higher-voltage appliance switching, integrate easily with Arduino systems and are widely used in smart home automation applications.
The relay modules allowed the microcontroller to safely control appliance switching operations without exposing the controller circuitry to high-voltage electrical loads. This improved both system safety and reliability during implementation and testing. (Ali Khan et al. 2024)
