5.4 Discussion of Findings
The findings demonstrate that low-cost IoT technologies can be effectively integrated to develop a functional smart home energy management system. The project successfully validated the use of embedded systems, wireless communication and mobile dashboards for appliance automation, monitoring and energy awareness.
The implemented system showed that RTC scheduling and real-time monitoring can improve appliance management while dashboard visualisation and notifications increase user awareness regarding energy consumption. The project additionally demonstrated that affordable hardware platforms such as Arduino can successfully support remote control, automation scheduling and IoT dashboard integration.
Iterative testing helped resolve issues relating to WiFi communication, relay behaviour and notification triggering, improving overall system reliability. The inclusion of physical user evaluation and Jisc survey feedback further strengthened the findings by providing practical usability validation alongside technical testing. (Aldossari and Sidorova 2018)
Overall, the results support the feasibility of using IoT-based automation systems to improve household energy management and encourage more energy-efficient appliance usage.
5.5 Answering the Research Question
The research question asked how an IoT-based smart home system combining remote control, real-time monitoring, RTC-based automation and energy management could reduce unnecessary power consumption and improve household energy efficiency.
The results demonstrate that the implemented system successfully reduced unnecessary appliance usage through automatic light activation and shutdown, fan auto-OFF functionality, scheduled all-device shutdown and reminder notifications. These features reduced reliance on manual appliance management and helped prevent devices from remaining active longer than required.
The system also improved energy awareness by providing real-time energy monitoring, live dashboard visualisation and energy-saving indicators. User evaluation results showed that 91% of participants agreed that the automation features reduced unnecessary energy usage, while 93% reported increased awareness of household energy consumption.
Therefore, the findings indicate that the proposed IoT-based smart home system successfully addressed the research question by combining automation, monitoring and user feedback mechanisms to support more energy-efficient appliance usage. (Condon et al. 2023)
5.6 Chapter Summary
This chapter presented the results obtained from the implementation, testing and user evaluation of the smart home energy management system. The developed prototype successfully demonstrated remote appliance control, PIR-based motion detection, RTC automation, notification services, energy monitoring and live dashboard visualisation.
System testing confirmed that the prototype operated reliably under real-time conditions and achieved the majority of the proposed project objectives. User evaluation sessions conducted at Southampton Solent University using a Jisc Online Survey questionnaire additionally indicated positive feedback regarding dashboard usability, automation effectiveness and energy monitoring functionality.
Overall, the results demonstrate that low-cost IoT and embedded technologies can be successfully integrated to develop an effective smart home automation and energy management solution for domestic environments.
