7. Limitations
This project successfully demonstrated the feasibility of a low-cost IoT-based smart home energy management system; however, several limitations were identified. Energy consumption values were estimated using predefined appliance power ratings rather than direct electrical measurements, which may affect accuracy. The prototype was evaluated within a single-room environment and may require further testing in larger residential settings. User evaluation was conducted with a relatively small sample size (n = 10), limiting the generalisability of the findings. In addition, the original machine learning and predictive automation objectives were not implemented due to project scope and hardware constraints. Finally, remote monitoring and mobile application functionality remain dependent on WiFi connectivity. (El Azab 2021)

 
8. Conclusions
This dissertation investigated the development of an IoT-based smart home energy management system designed to improve appliance control, support intelligent automation and increase user awareness of domestic energy consumption. The project aimed to develop a low-cost smart home prototype integrating remote device control, motion detection, RTC-based automation, notification services and real-time energy monitoring within a unified mobile platform.
The final implemented system successfully achieved the majority of the proposed objectives. The prototype demonstrated that embedded systems and IoT technologies can be effectively integrated to create a functional smart home environment capable of improving convenience, automation and energy efficiency. Technologies including Arduino, Blynk, PIR motion sensors, relay modules, servo motors and the DS3231 Real-Time Clock were successfully combined to support intelligent appliance management and real-time monitoring.
The developed system provided remote appliance control, motion detection, RTC-based scheduling, dynamic mobile configuration, notification services, energy monitoring and live dashboard visualisation. Testing confirmed that the system operated reliably under practical conditions, with stable automation, responsive device control and effective monitoring functionality.
An important addition to the project was the inclusion of physical user evaluation sessions conducted at Southampton Solent University. Participants interacted with the smart home prototype during live demonstrations and completed an anonymous Jisc Online Survey questionnaire. The collected feedback indicated positive responses regarding dashboard usability, automation responsiveness and energy monitoring features, providing additional validation of the system’s practicality and effectiveness.
Although the original proposal placed greater emphasis on predictive resource management and machine learning-based automation, the final system evolved towards a more practical rule-based automation and monitoring approach due to implementation constraints and project scope. Despite this, the project successfully achieved its broader objective of reducing unnecessary energy consumption through intelligent automation and monitoring technologies.
Overall, the project demonstrated that low-cost IoT technologies can be successfully used to develop an effective smart home energy management system capable of improving automation, increasing energy awareness and supporting energy-efficient behaviour within domestic environments.

 
9. Recommendations and Future Improvements
Although the implemented smart home energy management system successfully achieved its primary objectives, several improvements could further enhance the functionality, intelligence and scalability of the system in future development. One major improvement would be the integration of machine learning and predictive analytics to enable the system to learn user behaviour patterns automatically. Instead of relying mainly on rule-based automation and RTC scheduling, future versions could analyse occupancy trends, appliance usage habits and environmental conditions to make intelligent energy-saving decisions automatically. This would improve the predictive capabilities originally proposed in the project concept.
Another important enhancement would be the integration of voice assistant technologies such as Amazon Alexa or Google Assistant. Voice control functionality would allow users to operate appliances through spoken commands, improving accessibility and user convenience. For example, users could control lights, fans or door locking mechanisms through voice interactions without using the mobile dashboard directly.
The current system estimates energy consumption using appliance runtime and predefined power ratings. Future versions could improve accuracy by integrating dedicated current and voltage sensors capable of measuring real electrical usage directly from appliances. This would provide more precise monitoring data and allow advanced analysis of household energy consumption patterns.
Additional future improvements could include cloud-based data analytics and long-term data storage to support historical reporting and remote system access from multiple devices. Security enhancements such as biometric authentication, camera integration and encrypted communication protocols could also improve the safety and reliability of the smart home environment. Furthermore, the system could be expanded to support multi-room or full-house automation by integrating additional sensors, appliances and environmental monitoring devices such as smoke detectors, gas sensors and temperature control systems.
The project could also benefit from integration with renewable energy technologies such as solar panel monitoring and battery management systems. This would allow the smart home system to optimise appliance usage based on renewable energy availability and further improve energy efficiency.
Overall, the implemented prototype provides a strong foundation for future smart home development. With additional intelligent features, enhanced security and advanced automation capabilities, the system could evolve into a more scalable, predictive and commercially viable smart home energy management solution.
