E.1 Use case diagram:
The diagram identifies the primary functionalities available within the system and demonstrates how users interact with appliance control, automation and energy-monitoring features through the Blynk mobile application. The use case diagram represents how the user interacts with the smart home energy management system through the Blynk mobile application. The main actor is the user/homeowner, who can manually control the light, fan and door lock, monitor motion status, view energy usage, configure automation timings and receive notifications. The Arduino-based controller processes commands, sensor inputs and RTC-based automation rules to operate the connected devices.
E.2 Activity Diagram:
The diagram demonstrates how the system processes user commands, sensor inputs, RTC scheduling operations and automation logic during continuous system execution. The activity diagram illustrates the operational workflow of the smart home energy management system from system start-up to continuous monitoring and automation execution. Initially, the system initialises the Arduino controller, WiFi connection, Blynk platform and DS3231 RTC module. Once connectivity is established, the system continuously reads real-time clock values, PIR motion sensor data and user inputs from the Blynk mobile application.
The workflow supports both manual and automated operations. Users can remotely control the light, fan and door lock through the mobile dashboard, while the system simultaneously monitors RTC-based automation conditions such as automatic light activation, reminder notifications and scheduled all-device shutdown. Safety mechanisms are also implemented to automatically switch OFF appliances if they remain active beyond configured durations.
The system continuously calculates energy consumption and saved energy percentage based on appliance runtime and updates live gauges, charts and device status within the Blynk application. The process operates repeatedly in a continuous monitoring loop until the system is terminated.
E.3a RTC sequence diagram:
To further explain the automation behaviour of the proposed smart home system, an additional sequence diagram was developed focusing specifically on RTC-based scheduling and notification operations. The diagram demonstrates how the DS3231 RTC module, Arduino controller and Blynk platform interact to perform automatic appliance control, reminder notifications and scheduled shutdown operations.
The sequence diagram illustrates the interaction between the DS3231 RTC module, Arduino controller, Blynk mobile application and connected appliances during automated system operation. The Arduino controller continuously reads the current time from the RTC module and compares it with user-configured automation schedules stored within the Blynk platform.
When the configured automation time is reached, the system automatically performs actions including light activation, reminder notification generation and scheduled all-device shutdown. The Arduino controller then updates the Blynk dashboard with the latest appliance status and automation information.
The diagram additionally demonstrates how the smart home system supports continuous monitoring, real-time dashboard updates and automatic notification delivery through the Blynk cloud platform.
E.3b Energy monitoring sequence diagram:
The sequence diagram illustrates the interaction between the user, Blynk mobile application, Arduino controller and energy calculation module during real-time monitoring operations. The Arduino controller continuously checks the operating status of connected appliances including the light and fan and calculates energy consumption based on runtime and predefined power ratings.
The system then calculates the saved energy percentage and transmits the updated information to the Blynk dashboard. Live gauges and charts within the mobile application are continuously refreshed to provide users with real-time visualisation of appliance activity and energy usage trends.





